<DOC><DOCNO> AP890302-0219 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 2131EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-02 0597</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0618</SECOND><HEAD>Snowstorm Hits the Pacific Northwest, Moving East</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A major winter storm brought strong winds, heavy rain and snowThursday to parts of the Pacific Coast, with heavy snow forecast formuch of the western states through Friday.   Heavy snow in the Seattle area shut down the Seattle-Tacomaairport for about 15 hours, but it reopened by mid-morning Thursday.Snowfall ranged from 8 inches to 16 inches in the Auburn area, justsouth of Seattle.   Heavy rainfall fell on parts of Northern California, with morethan 3{ inches recorded at Ross, just north of San Francisco, andmore than 2{ inches at Redding.   More than a foot of snow fell in the Sierra Nevada, where windsgusted to 50 to 70 mph, and the higher elevations of extreme westernNevada.   Heavy snow also fell on portions of the northern Rockies, whereabout 12 inches fell overnight in the ski areas near Jackson Hole,Wyo.   Winter storm warnings were in effect for southern and easternOregon, central Idaho, northwest Wyoming, much of the Sierra Nevadain California and higher elevations of northern and central Nevada.   Winter storm warnings for heavy snow were expected by Fridayacross most of the mountains of Idaho and western Wyoming. Winterstorm watches were posted for south central Montana, northern andcentral Wyoming and the mountains of Colorado.   High wind warnings for wind gusts to over 60 miles an hour coverall of Nevada.   Frigid weather covered the northern Plains, where temperatureswere below zero Thursday in parts of Montana, North Dakota andMinnesota, for wind chills ranging as low as 40 below zero.   Freezing drizzle was mixed with snow over southern Nebraska.   In western New York, snow continued to be locally heavy east ofLake Ontario, with 22 inches of snowfall recorded at Barnes Corners,N.Y., since snow began wednesday,   Rain covered the South Atlantic and Gulf coastal states.Thunderstorms over the Gulf of Mexico dumped marble-size hail nearGulf Shores, Ala.   Partly cloudy skies and dry weather prevailed from New Englandand the mid-Atlantic states across the Ohio Valley to the southernhalf of the Great Plains.   Dense fog was reported this morning from western texas acrosswestern kansas and eastern colorado to southeast wyoming.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 6degrees below zero at Warroad, Minn., to 84 degrees at Fort Myers,Fla.   The national weather forecast for Friday predicted snowwidespread from the northern and central Plateau across the northernand central Rockies, the northern half of the Great Plains, upperMississippi Valley and the Great Lakes to much of New England. Snowwill be mixed with freezing rain for Iowa and eastern Nebraska. Rainwill occur over much of California, Arizona and northern New Mexico,and from Kansas and Oklahoma to the middle Mississippi and Ohiovalleys. Rainshowers will be scattered across the Carolinas, withthunder storms over Florida. Widely scattered thunderstorms willoccur over the lower Mississippi Valley.   High temperatures will be in the teens and 20s from easternWashington state across Montana, the northern half of the GreatPlains and the upper Mississippi Valley to the upper Great Lakes,and across northern New England.   Temperatures will reach the 50s and 60s in California, the desertSouthwest, New Mexico, southern Kansas and the middle Mississippiand Ohio valleys to the middle and south Atlantic coastal states;the 80s over much of Texas, the 70s over the lower MississippiValley, and the 70s to mid-80s in Florida. Elsewhere, highs will bein the 30s and 40s.</TEXT></DOC>